segments.text: June the 4th, 1896.
We are in College Station, Texas, in the offices of the Chemical Engineering Department.
Ron, could you tell me a little bit about your personal biography, your background, how you came to be at Texas A&M?
Hey, Ron, it's June the 6th, Wednesday, June the 6th, 1996.
And you're talking about the history and development of the Department of Chemical Engineering.
And if you would, would you please tell me your name for the record and a little biographical information about your upbringing and your early education and how you finally got to A&M?
OK. Ron Darby.
I was born on September 12, 1932, in La Vida, Colorado.
My father was actually, he was an educator at the time.
He was teaching school, but later became more of a traveling salesman.
So we moved a lot in my early years.
In fact, I never lived in any one place more than three years until I went to college.
But I went to grade school.
In fact, I lived in Bryan in 1938, 39, and went to grade school here one semester in Bryan back then.
Did most of my grade schooling in Houston, a little bit in Waco, and then junior high in Beaumont, some in Houston and Beaumont, and then moved to Atlanta, Georgia for high school.
Graduated from high school in Atlanta in 1950.
And then I applied for the Naval ROTC program when I was in high school, and it's a scholarship program.
And you have to put down a choice of where you want to go to school, three choices for second and third.
And I'd actually put down Georgia Tech and Rice and Duke in that order.
But then I got to thinking I'd want to come back to Texas.
So I went down and changed my preference and put down Rice first and then Georgia Tech and Duke.
So I ended up going to Rice.
It's different.
You know, that's why I went to Texas in ROTC.
Is that right?
Sure is.
I got there in 52.
That was exactly the reason.
Tulane, I think, had ROTC in Louisiana.
You go to high school in Louisiana?
Yeah.
Well, if I hadn't changed my mind, I'd have gone to Georgia Tech.
Of course, I'd grown up a lot in Houston, and I wanted to go back to Texas.
So I went to Rice on an ROTC scholarship.
There was a five-year engineering BS program at the time, so it was five years for a BS degree.
And, of course, the rules of the ROTC were that as soon as you get a degree, you have to get your commission and go on active duty.
And Rice normally gave a BA after four years and a BS after five years, so I had to delay the BA degree until after my fifth year so I wouldn't have to go on active duty.
So at the end of my fifth year, I got a BA and a BS and a commission all at the same time.
Where'd you go?
Well, I went on destroyers in the Pacific.
Actually, before I graduated, I had a round of interviews because I wanted to pin down a job to go to, and I got out of the Navy.
So I talked to companies all over the country, mostly East Coast and West Coast and Texas and Oklahoma.
And I picked a job with Dow Chemical in Freeport.
And I actually went down there for about three weeks before I had to report to my ship after I graduated.
And so I had kind of an orientation program.
At that time, you'd have, actually, you were on their rolls, so you had three years of longevity for your Navy service.
It was three years after duty.
That's right, three years, because you were a full-time sergeant.
I had two years.
And in fact, being the destroyers in the Pacific, I requested destroyers in the Pacific.
I remember I got courier duty in the Atlantic in the National Naval Air Force.
Is that right?
Which was really great, but still, that's not what I'd asked for.
Well, that's what I'd asked for, and I got it.
So anyway, I was reported to a destroyer, a structure class destroyer in San Diego in 1955 when I graduated.
And I was on that for a couple of years with...
Two or three trips to Westpac, I was electronics officer and officer of the deck, CIC officer, all in operations on the destroyer, and also a navigator.
In fact, I was officer of the deck for general quarters and had a division officer and navigator.
ended up relieving myself on the watch more often than not.
It was good.
It was a good experience.
I really enjoyed it.
Two or three trips to Westpac.
On one of them, we went to Brisbane, Australia, and we were the first ships since the end of World War II into Brisbane.
And the Australians really went all out.
We had more parties to go to than we had people to go to in Brisbane.
It was a lot of fun.
And then, of course, the usual Hong Kong, Philippines,
Japan, and so forth.
What was that, the big base in Japan?
Yakuska.
Yakuska.
Yeah, in and out of Yakuska and Kobe.
But then after a couple years on that, I was transferred to a commissioning detail for a radar picket ship.
Her ship was the Chandler 717.
Of course, Charlie Holland had been in the Navy, so...
He liked to tell some stories, too.
But anyway, the Chandler, this was the Newell 322, was originally a World War II destroyer escort that had been mothballed and then resurrected in Korea as a weather ship to the Coast Guard.
And then it was mothballed again in Florida.
And then they towed it around to Long Beach and put it in commission as a radar picket ship.
And I was the CIC officer there in charge of all the electronics equipment and the radars and all of that.
And we had, at the time, the state-of-the-art radars.
Of course, the long-range air search radars, the objective was to serve picket duty out in the Pacific for long-range search.
Were you offshore a lot?
Well, I spent about six months in Long Beach putting the thing in commission.
And then it was stationed at Pearl Harbor.
So I was at Pearl for six months.
And during that period, we had one picket tour, which really ran from Midway to Kodiak, Alaska.
So we ran back and forth there for about three weeks.
And then that's the only tour I had before I got out.
And then when I got out, I got out in May of 58.
And meanwhile, I decided I wanted to go back to graduate school because a lot of stuff that I'd like to know, I didn't know.
and I wanted to get more training and education.
So I wrote to Dow and asked them...
Excuse me, your degree from Rice, your B.S.
was in... Chemical Engineering.
Chemical Engineering.
So actually I have a B.A.
and a B.S.
in Rice.
The B.A.
is undesignated, but the B.S.
is here.
So I wrote to Dow and asked them if I could just come down and work for the summer until classes started in September.
And they said, yeah, that's okay, no problem.
So I went down there the first of June, reported for work,
And they called me in, and this was in 1958, and that was the biggest downturn the chemical industry has ever had.
I mean, before or since, that was the recession.
And Dow had been given a mandate to lay off 10% of the employees across the board in every division.
So they called me and said, look, we're laying people off.
We really can't take you on this summer.
We're very sorry.
Here's $300 severance pay.
Good luck.
So they sent me home with $300 in my pocket.
And I went back to Houston, and I got a job that summer working for Bill Akers, who was head of the kidney department at Rice.
He had a consulting project having to do with heat transfer and heavy oils in him, too.
So me and another student worked on that that summer, and it was a good experience.
I remember when I was a student, my students were geology, I guess, exploration.
Yeah, it hit them hard.
Oh, there was no marketplace then.
That's right.
It really wiped it out.
But anyway, I was in graduate school at Rice then until 61.
I finished all my work actually in late 60, in the fall of 60.

finished it actually in october got married in december and i got married in november and in december my wife and i left on a freighter for england i applied for a nsf postdoc scholarship which i got for a year in england in cambridge and they gave a total of six cents travel
for one person to get to where you were going.
So I shopped around for the cheapest way to get to England, which was a freighter.
So I booked us on a Lykes freighter to go to England, which was an experience.

The rules said that you had to leave from the last US port and get off at the first UK port, but they wouldn't tell you where that was because it's basically unscheduled, so you have to change at the last minute.
And sure enough, this freighter was supposed to leave from Galveston,
but they changed their schedule and they went to Galveston, but they had to go to Corpus to pick up some freight.
So we had to, even though we were in Houston, the freighter was in Galveston, we had to go to Corpus to get on the ship.
And it was a two-week trip from Corpus to Liverpool.
And we got to Liverpool in the middle of December and then went to Cambridge.
And that was a fun time.
I did a research project there with a fellow on nuclear oil.
studying the rate of growth of bubbles in a nuclear boiling system.
And that was my first kind of independent research project.
And that was a lot of fun.
We traveled around, took a couple trips on the continent and all, bought a British car,
The place we went, they thought we were British, so that was... One year.
Yeah, exactly a year.
Came back the following December, and it was a really cold year.

We had a flat in Cambridge that was heated electrically, and our electric bills were kind of high, and we asked our landlady why they were so high, and my wife did, and the landlady says, well, my dear...
can I ask you a personal question?
She said, well, I guess so.
She said, well, just how often do you bathe?
We had an electrified water heater and everything.
She says, well, we bathe every day.
She says, my dear, don't you realize you're washing all the natural oils out of your skin?
I think once a week is a norm.
So anyway, she was a great landlady.
When we left there, actually, she owed us a little return on our
deposit, which she sent a check for pounds, which I couldn't negotiate in the bank.
So I sent it back to her and asked her if she would use, please use that money to buy me a book.
And I told her what book I wanted.
She did.
She bought the book and she sent it to me.
So it was a long time.
But then after I came back from England, I, actually before I went to England, before I knew that I had the NSF post-doc scholarship, I had gone through some interviews to pin down a job.
And I

concentrated mostly on texas and oklahoma at that time but then when i got the scholarship and i went to england i came back and i had another round of interviews so that's my third interviewing round and i i took a job with lean temp cobalt ltv research center in grand prairie and that was during jimmy lane's heyday you probably remember jimmy lane he was notorious they say that jimmy lane never actually graduated from high school
But he put together such complicated financing deals with all these companies that he bought and sold that a lot of people couldn't understand that it was so complicated.
And a lot of people wondered if Jimmy understood it himself.
But he was an amazing guy.
So he was on the same deal with you?
Oh, yeah.
I met Jimmy.
I talked to Jimmy.
And he was an interesting guy.
But I was working on the fuel cell research at the time.
LTV, of course, in the space and aircraft business, wanted to have some expertise in fuel cells, even though they didn't have any production facilities for them.
They needed to keep abreast of that technology, so that's basically why I was doing that.
But one year, LTV would decide they were going to diversify, so Jimmy went out and he bought up Friedrich Air Conditioners and a bunch of other companies that didn't necessarily relate to aerospace.
Then the next year, they decided they were going to specialize
So they sold off all these companies to concentrate on government business.
So it was going back and forth.
Yeah, I remember watching the LTV.
Yeah, it was Wheeler Dealer.
In fact, Jimmy Lane made his, the word was that he made his fortune in World War II.
He was an electrical contractor, and he bought up a lot of surplus aluminum cables from Chance Law Aircraft Company at like pennies on the dollar.
and he made a killing by marketing that cable, and he ended up buying the company he bought the cable from.
I've heard people doing that with iron, you know, just all iron.
Yeah, scrap iron.
But anyway, when I was in graduate school at Rice, Leo Durbin and I and two other graduate students roomed together in a two-bedroom apartment,
So Leo and I shared one bedroom, and the other two guys shared another bedroom.
And Leo graduated, he started the year before I did, and he graduated a little earlier than I did, and he wanted to go into teaching.
So Leo actually wanted to go to work for the University of Texas, and he went over and he had an interview with John McKetta.
And John is really an interesting guy.
Everybody loves John.
But John always said later,

that he really wanted to hire Leo except during the interview Leo went to sleep when he was talking to them and so he couldn't he couldn't offer him a job because he went to sleep during the interview but anyway Leo was hired here played back huh yeah John McKetta M-C-K-E-T-T-A yeah John McKetta he's a classic over there
He's still active.
He's retired, but he's still...
He recently gave a million dollars to the community department.
Who was that?
He gave them a big party and all that.
He was editor of a book series, and I published my first book, so I knew him.
But anyway, Leo was hired here at A&M while I was off in England.
I was working here.
When I went to work for LTV, I wrote up a paper on the research that I did in England on nuclear boiling.
and published it in Chemical Engineering Science.
And Leo saw the paper, and they were looking for a new faculty member, so Leo put my name in the pod with Lindsey and Holland.
So Holland called me, and I'd always kind of wanted to get into teaching.
In fact, even when I was in the Navy, I set up kind of some instruction courses for the electronics technicians to try to teach them some basic electricity and stuff.
And I enjoyed all that, so I really wanted to get into it.
So, but really, it was not your initiative so much.
No, that's right.
I just got a call out of the blue one day from Leo wanting to know if I was interested in a teaching job.
Let me back up.
When you were interviewing that person in his early years out of Rice, what were you looking at?
What was happening, going on in Texas that particularly related to chemical engineers?
Well, I guess that was kind of a heyday of chemical engineering in a way, because the chemical engineers were
The cream of the crop of the students in most universities, they were top notch and getting the best jobs.
And the chemical industry was really mushrooming all over the place.
It was in really a growth mode.
And actually, I was looking more for location than specific jobs.
I had interviews all the way from Standard Oil in New Jersey and DuPont in Delaware to Chevron in California.
Dow and Texaco, mostly petroleum oil companies and petrochemical companies.
I talked with Dow.
I had several job offers from Exxon and Texaco.
A lot of them were petroleum production areas and those were like engineering and stuff like that.
In fact, when I went to work for
I kind of like the Dallas area, so my last rounds I was kind of concentrating on Dallas or Oklahoma.
I like Dallas and Tulsa, so I kind of concentrated on companies in those two towns.
And I had a job offer from Mobile Field Research Laboratory outside of Dallas in Duncanville, which was a nice job.
I was really torn between that and LTV.
But LTV looked a little more exotic, a little different.
Yeah, very, very.
Yeah, a little more.
avant-garde, I guess, or whatever, so I thought I'd try that, which may or may not have been a good thing.
I published two or three papers on the work that I did up there, so it came out okay on the fuel cell stuff I was doing, mostly on theoretical models and stuff.
But then I got this call from Leo, and so I decided to follow up on it, and came down for an interview, and
They offered me the job, so I decided to take it.
Did you take a pay cut?
Yeah, I did.
I would think so.
Yeah, I took, I guess, about 20% pay cut when I came here tonight.
So that was it.
Was that a good idea?
Well, she pretty well went along with what I wanted.
Meanwhile, we had our first child was born in Dallas.
She was born...
just about a week before Kennedy was killed.
And then we moved from there in 65.
Then we had another one after we came here in 66.
Second,
Her son was born in April of 66, and we've got two kids.
My wife died of cancer in 89, and my kids now are growing and growing.
Where are they now?
Well, my daughter is married, and she and her husband are in graduate school at Virginia Tech.
She got an accounting degree here, and then they both worked for a while in Florida, and she picked up an MBA degree at Florida Atlantic University over there.
And they decided they wanted to get into academic English.
I had never suspected.
Yeah, you never know about that.
My son's just moved here this past year.
He's working with me in education.
Is that right?
Well, my daughter wanted to.
I thought he wanted to be a coach.
Yeah.
Well, that's what my son wants to do.
In fact, he got his degree here in kinesiology and a minor in biology.
And he always wanted to be a basketball player.
Carl did.
And he coached me back at Coppell.
Did he?
couple of years and did a nice job.
His wife didn't like it up there.
Well, my son moved to Houston, got a job in a junior high school in the Spring School of History, Spring Bank School of History, which was actually mostly a minority area.
But he coached basketball and some football.
And then he got married to a girl who had a master's degree in veterinary pharmacology here in Houston.
And she was working with MD Anderson down there at the time.
And she got a good job offer from Eli Willey up in Indiana, just outside of Indianapolis.
So they moved up there.
And actually, they split up last year, about a year ago.
So he's on his own.
He's still up there in Greenfield.
He's outside of Indianapolis.
He taught for a while there.
In fact, he had one year in the Indianapolis School District in the inner city school.
which was a pure nightmare.
I mean, the kids were wild, uncontrolled, no discipline, and it was just terrible.
He got out of his class as a kid, but he hasn't gotten a permanent teaching job since.
He's been working for the city of Greenfield in their recreation department.
He supervises their softball leagues.
all their athletic competition and stuff like that.
Well, I think he's kind of torn.
He kind of likes it there, and he's used to it there.
He's got a lot of inertia.
He's not very adventurous.
He hasn't rejected them.
It's hard to get a job long distance, particularly teaching jobs.
You pretty well have to be on the spot and make a lot of contacts to get in the system.
He's been trying to get back in the school system over the years.
He also has a second job with a boys club.
So he's got kind of two part-time jobs, basically.
I bet you he'll get back in.
My daughter always liked the applied areas in business.
So she wanted to get in a program where she could teach applications in business.
She actually taught a little bit in a vocational program in Florida when she was in there.
Then she found a program
in the voc-ed department at Virginia Tech that had a business class here.
So that sounded good to her, so she enrolled in that.
She was in there for a couple years.
She actually got a doctorate of education degree through that program.
But she was really disappointed with the standards in the voc-ed program.
She said she had fellow graduate students that she didn't know whether they could walk or chew gum at the same time.
And that was really poor.
In fact, since then, just about the time she got her degree,
Virginia Tech, as part of their budget control procedures, wiped out the College of Education, the whole college.
The whole College of Education?
Yeah, the whole College of Education.
So meanwhile, she had transferred back into the business college, and she's working on a PhD in strategic management now.
And her husband got a master's degree here in landscape architecture, and he's working on a PhD in landscape architecture there.
And it's kind of ironic because
His father lost his wife to cancer about a year before I did.
And then he and my daughter got together and got married.
And then his father was on the faculty here in architecture, Ralph Eccleston.
And so he was, in fact, he and I share a common birthday.
He's three years older than I am, but we were born on the same day of the year.
And he had a second marriage, which didn't work out.
And I had a second marriage, which didn't work out.
And so he actually moved into my house and lived there for a couple of years with me and my house.
He was actually on a nine-month appointment, so he went back to Virginia in the summertime and then decided just to go ahead and retire this past year.
So he's back there full-time.

His family, and I was raised from Virginia, of course, my wife's, his son, my wife's husband, has got three brothers and a sister, and all of them went on the back of Virginia there, so most of them are family ties.
Yeah.
It's interesting to see what happens to your kid.
Yeah.
And you don't know why.
Their life is more complicated than ours, I think, though, I don't know.
But you kind of ask, why did I get into chemical engineering?
And I tell students this a lot.
Because when I was in high school, my favorite course actually, well, I had three favorite courses.
I liked my mechanical drawing course.
I had a good chemistry course, and I probably learned more from the typing course than anything else from the practical matter.
I had the same experience.
Is that right?
I had drawing.
I loved it.
And typing.
I had two or three years of drawing.
I loved it.
And typing.
I was good at typing.
My typing instructor told me she thought it would be a good idea if I dropped the class at a certain point because she knew I wouldn't be making very good grades.
or something, and so I dropped it.
But it was a good experience.
I got up to over 60 words a second in that typing course, which just came in a lot of really handy.
But I was kind of the teacher's pet in the chemistry course.
I'll never forget my high school chemistry teacher.
His name was Haichi, very unusual name.
Haichi?
I think he was Slavic or something.
H-I-T-C-H-E-W.
I'm not sure exactly.
But he was a crusty old character.
It was a good course.
But actually, I envisioned myself as being mechanically inclined.
In fact, I thought at one time I wanted to work as an architect.
And I worked one summer when I was in high school for an architect.
And when I saw what was involved, I decided I wanted to be an architect, which was good.
But then when I went to college, I was leaning toward mechanical engineering.
But at Rice, you didn't have to prepare a major to your sophomore year.
You just divided people into science, engineering, and liberal arts.
Two categories.
So I went through the science, engineering route.
And while I was there, the word around the campus was that chem engineering was the toughest program on the campus.
It was the most challenging.
So I said, by God, I think I'll try it to see if I can do it.
So I got into it more as a challenge than anything else.
Of course, I did like my chemistry course, but I wasn't really all that in love with chemistry.
But it was a challenge, and I got into it, and I enjoyed it.
But I'm kind of a frustrated mechanical engineer, probably more than anything else.
I probably use more physics than chemistry in the stuff I've done, because I'm more into fluid mechanics, and rheology, and viscoelastic materials, and , and stuff.
There's a lot more physics involved than chemistry .
And in some places, I've been doing some background reading, chemical engineering really came out of physics departments.
Some places gave them petroleum, and in some places, of course, a lot of places, as here, chemical departments.
Well, you know, back when I was in school, there was not that much of a distinction between a physical chemist and a chemical engineer.
In fact, in Europe, they don't make a lot of distinction.
They have chemical physics and physical chemistry and chem engineers, and they all are more or less the same kind of thing with a little different slant.
They're all very applied programming.
And physical chemistry used to be an applied course where you actually learned about vapor-liquid equilibrium and surface tension and diffusivity and practical physical properties.
And it was a good, useful course for chemical engineers.
But physical chemistry now has gotten so esoteric that all they want to do is talk about spectral analysis, energy levels, quantum mechanics, statistical mechanics, and things like that.
And it doesn't deal so much with the tangibles anymore like it used to.
Has chemical engineering changed in its
context approach and its clientele, let's say, here at A&M.
Chemical engineering hasn't undergone any revolutionary, drastic changes.
It's undergone a lot of evolutionary changes, but no real revolutionary.
Again, of course, there's always more information.
You try to cram more and more into the curriculum, but you've got to take something out when you put something in.
So the curriculum...
Things that used to be taught in graduate school now are moved down to senior level, just like high school.
When we were going through school, nobody took calculus until they got to college.
Now, most all high school kids are taking calculus.
So that kind of thing is permeating the whole system.
But I think I have seen a change in the students since I've been here for 30 years.
You probably saw a change, too.
When I first came, the enrollment of A&M was about 8,000 students, and it was largely a rural-type atmosphere.
Most of the students were from rural or small-town environments.
They had a strong work ethic.
They might not have been the superstars in the classroom,
down to the kids.
We still get quite a few of those.
But now we're probably drawing a lot more from the urban areas.
I guess Harris County provides more students than any other place else.
And so we have more students.
You know, that's what Lindsey said.
He called it a country boy school.
But, you know, with respect, he said most of the kids were first-generation college students.
And so they were
That's right.
I think that's been a strong deprivation.

In fact, one of our former students, who was in one of my first classes that I taught when I was here, who is a well-respected manager for Dow now, was on our advisory committee for some time, and paid sure to conduct a survey at Dow one time,
to see if there were any correlations between the grades student made in school and their performance on the job after they went to work.
And they found that there was no correlation at all with grades.

But he said that there was somewhat of a correlation between their job performance and their socioeconomic background, in that the students that came from the rural and small town environments tended to do better than those that came from urban environments.
That's interesting.
But there was no correlation there with grades.
In fact, there's the old story, you know, that when you graduate, the A students will work for the C students.
Probably because the C students had to work harder to get their grades than the A students did.
And that work ethic meant more on the job than the actual grades.
And I think that's becoming more important now.
And the students are realizing it less.
The students are putting a lot more emphasis on getting grades than learning.
Whereas in previous years, they would put the emphasis on learning.
And if the grade came, that's OK.
But the main thing was to learn the material.
Now the main thing is to get a grade.
And if they learn something, that's OK.
But the main thing is to get that grade.
So the emphasis has changed a lot.
And I guess, too, in part, that's because the deck's stacked that way.
Yeah, that's right.
The system drives it.
A good C student was as employable as an A student.
That's right.
In fact, the A&M regulations now define A as excellent, B as good, C as satisfactory.
They used to have numericals, but they don't have that anymore.
But unfortunately, a lot of students and a lot of instructors look at C's as unsat grades because a student with a C average graduating has a hard time getting a job.
So they look at C as basically unsat.
And I'm afraid that we're turning some students out that are really unsat that have C averages.
So, anyway, that's one of my soapboxes.
It's way inflation.
Yeah.
The guy's name is without a shirt?
Page.
Page.
Page.
S-H-I-R-T-E-N.
Oh, there's probably a few of them, I guess.
come through mine, but you kind of lose track of them.
Yeah, sure.
Not many of them that I have really followed.
I know this guy, and I didn't interview him, but David Chapman did.
Jim Mathis.
Jim Mathis.
Yeah.
I think he was before my time as far as being a student.
He was on our direct advisor.
In fact, we had another
a former student who was on our advisory committee.
But when he went through school, he always said that my course was the best course that he had.
It's really one of the more practical courses.
And after he graduated, he actually sent me back $275 donations directly to me for support of my
my research project.
And that's the only grant that I've had that was a personal thing just for me.
And it was right out of his pocket, sending it to me.
What do you talk most of the time?
Well, fluid mechanics, actually I taught... That's the basic fluid mechanics course?
Right, junior level fluid mechanics.
I taught that more than anyone else.
That's my baby, so to speak.
In fact, I just published my second book, which is Chemical Engineering and Fluid Mechanics, which is an outgrowth of teaching that course for 30 years.
It's got several hundred problems in the book, most of which are old exam problems from previous exams.
You have a lot of, I'm sure, non-chemical engineers, all engineers coming in.
No, this is just for chemical engineers.
Actually, it covers a lot of stuff that the other...
fluid mechanics courses don't cover like in civil and mechanical.
They have their own fluids courses.
We get into not only flows and pipes and pumps and tanks and pressure vessels and stuff, but we also cover non-Newtonian, Newtonian, and compressible fluids and gases.
And we also cover fluid-solid separations like falling particles and sedimentation and filters and fluid ion states and things like that.
So it's a pretty good scope of material.

but i've i've taught everything from freshman to graduate students well actually since i came here i've started probably seven or eight courses from scratch i started a graduate course in rheology which is my primary research area i started undergraduate courses in polymer engineering
and corrosion and electrochemical engineering and transport phenomena.
I taught and started a graduate course, also an undergraduate course in process safety engineering.
Graduate courses in process safety engineering and applied electrochemistry and polymer engineering.
